 when I was younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever have any things like muffin men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes, jingle - oh yes, the muffin man every Sunday afternoon, winkles and shrimps come round ringing the bells. Muffin man used to ring the bell. Used to have this thing on top of
 his head. And you'd get muffins off of him and they were - lovely muffins. They used to be four a penny. Four a penny, not like today. Well they're not muffins today, they're terrible. They're shocking. The same as a salad, there's not a bit of - nourish
m
ent in the salad - there's no taste, not like when my father had his shops. Used to be beautiful and we used to love our salad. But today - no taste at all. If I was going out I wouldn't have a salad. When we do go out. I eat it because very rude to leave
. Mostly leave a bit, especially the lettuce because - all those chemicals they put in 'em today - takes all the vitamins out of 'em. Takes all the goodness out of stuff.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would your mother make her own things like pickles or bottle jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. 
No. Never nothing like that, never used to eat things - no, it was all bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Do you remember whether - how often a week you'd have meat in those days?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes, Sundays we used to have beef, we might - meat on a Fri - n
o, not meat on a Friday. Fish Friday. Yes. Used to have meat on a Wednesday. Twice a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Sunday and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Wednesday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What would you have for high dinner the other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh well we'd have - something perhaps the woman's made - a - a - sa
y a steak and kidney pudding or - 'course it used to be nice steak and kidney pudding those days, or meat pudding, or meat pie - nice rice puddings. All those kind of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 But you'd have a hot meal in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Hot meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 And salad ain the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
That's right, but I don't - we used to like the salad those days as I tell you and I used to eat 'em and enjoy 'em, with cold ham. 'Cos I didn't like that. We used to boil the ham those days like - they used to have the hocks and boil them
. Not the ham that you buy at the shops today. And it used to be beautiful, the knuckles, what they used to call the knuckles. We used to get and boil.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You'd be on tap for all these kind of things being a market }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 type}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  area?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes, def - oh yes,
 well father used to get them - a bit - you know, a bit cheaper for the simple reason that - if we had customers come in for - for fruit, they used to like - what would you say - like a discount or - something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever have any sort of tinned food at all in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Tin? Can't remember any tinned stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Or dried vegetables at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. Oh no. No, no dried stuff. No, no, nothing like that. -Used to have nice faggots, those days, pease pudding. Make yourself. The pease pudding, the - mum used to make it herself with the peas but it used to take a hell of a long time 'cos peas were -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would she eat with you when she'd cooked it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Yes. Sometimes, yes. I always used to like to go in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 kitchen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  and eat with - t
he lady. Because I - I'd like - yes, but I know I always liked to get - eat in the kitchen but of my course my dad wouldn't have that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 She'd even come in for breakfast and eat breakfast with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Oh yes. Oh my father treated her as one of his own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 But she didn't actually live in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No, she lived out, just ordinary daily woman - like woman used to come three times. 'Cos mother wouldn't - mother never used to do the housework at all. She used to do - and she used to do sewing.
 She used to go into - Lincolns Inn Fields - and sit in the gardens there. Yes. And she used to do knit - knitting or sewing there. And - I - of course the school wasn't far from there, I used to come out of the school and she'd be sitting in the garden w
a
iting for me. I always remember that. It's beautiful there Lincoln Inn Fields there in the - gardens there. Yes. And - and also, I don't know if you know - in - Theobalds Road, you know Theobalds Road at all? Do you know where the trams go down under the 
a
rches? The little road - that's still - I think they're still now, well how - the quickest way would be to get to that. You get off St Pancras Church, Euston Road - you cut up - St Pancras Church, go straight ahead, and - you'd come to Theobalds Road. The
r
e'd be a big fire station on the right hand side, go further along and there'd be like a - archway, and little tiny trams. People ride in 'em. And they go underneath the archway to get to the other side. I don't know if - I haven't been up that way for a 
l
ong time whether they're still there or not, but I would love to go and find out and see if they're still there. But they've been there for years - years that - really - only short tr- trams they were you know, old people you'd get in and - doors'd swing 
a
long just the same, and - yes - you want to go there and see if they're still there, it's very interesting to see the people - well if they're still there the people still ride in them of course but as I say I haven't been that way for quite a while, down
 - Theobalds Road way or - Shewsbury Avenue and all round there, I haven't been that way. But it was quite nice. Used to be quite nice when I - lived round there. I used to like it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So there were lots of places to go and see when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes, hell of a lots of place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you go on many picnics and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No. Never picnics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go on holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes. I went to - used to go to Whitstable, Kent, fortnight, every year. Or sometimes - I'd g
o to another place, I couldn't exactly tell you the name but I know I used to go away, and - used to go with other children. They used to do it from the school, so that father could send us from the school. Fortnight each week - each year. Yes. Went to Wh
itstable and - Tankerton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Where's that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
That's - on Kent line. That's Kent line, and very nice, we used to be right on top of the water. See all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go on any holidays with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. Never on holiday with -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did they ever take holidays themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Very seldom. Very seldom. I think my mother did when she - we found that mother was - getting a bit weak - she went to convalescent to Folkesone. And she went down, she stayed there for quite a while. Sh
e came back - got better. And she got this - double pneumonia, must have caught a chill just - all of a sudden through something or the other, why she got it I don't know 'cos I mean there was every attention. She used to have all she wanted or anything '
c
os she never drank or nothing. And - but she had plenty of nourishing food to keep her going. But as I say it was to be. I know she died of double pneumonia and bronchitis with it. She - as I say, she was young. Quite young. It really upset my dad, and my
 dad was - ill for quite a while over it, when we lost my mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 It's quite a loss at that time isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Do you ever remember your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Could you have what you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. No, had what I wanted. No, I could have what I wanted. Like in regards to - if you mean - I had to have what he said - I would. Whatever he had on the table we - you'd have to eat. Oh yes, there'd be no - different dishes. Oh no, yo
u had to have what eh put there. And the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 majority}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
 of the food that was put there we always used to like. If he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What order were you served in at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Beg pardon? Oh - the youngest was always last. That'd be me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Where did you sit before you were old enough to sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I used to sit at the side of my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Who would do the serving up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well dad - my father used to do most of it about - if the lady was there - she'd help out, you know, when mother began to get ill, she used to help out, help my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
When you had a birthday would it be a special day or would it be like any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh no, there'd be a special day for me. I'd have just - local children in, say about - twelve of us. And - birthday c
ake and all that kind of thing, you know, and - little presents. We used to give all the other little kiddies. And - then we'd have a - then have tea and enjoy ourselves in our own way. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would you have birthday cards and things like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, plenty of birthday cards, oh yes, from - dad's customers as well, and people that used to come and trade. But we - I never used to tell 'em, used to me my father'd say - daughter's birthday tomorrow, something like that, and I used to get car
ds and - little bits of - presents, you know. Small }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 articles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
 those days, not very big, but - to us children they - it was fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How would you spend Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - we'd have a family party, you know, like - we do today, all get together like the family. And - couple of outsiders, strangers, like the businessmen and - that'd be all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of things would you do Christmas day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well Christmas Day we'd do what we like I think. Children were allowed to - in their own way, in their own place, but we were allowed to mix in the evening. But during the day after dinner or anything like that we were allowed to - do as we like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would the people who came stay to dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Yes, that's right, in the evening we always together - all together.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 That would be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 mainly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  relatives would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. Mostly relatives and - few of my father's - relations, something like that. A few of his friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did your relatives pop in very much during the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. Because we used to live a distance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 They used to live in Newmarket didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Newmarket, yes, couldn't come then - and one was in Fulham, and Walthamstow, there so that - might come once a year. That's about all. Used to see 'em 'cos father never had time to go over there to see them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 When did he get his car?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 When did he get his car?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes, I know, I couldn't remember, funny old thing I know. Bit - big wheels with a - big top too, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would he take you out in it very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, and he used to take me out in the - horse buses. They used to have horse buses those days. Drawn by horses. Four horses. And - and when mother died as I tell her her funeral be the horses then used to wear plumes on their head with th
e big velvets }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 hanging}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
 at the side and always used to be four - to draw the coach, I can remember that too, quite plainly, black, velvet. But - that - of course them - cars those days were very very funny to today cars. You have seen 'em sometimes - when th
ey've - done a run to Brighton. Can't you. Yes. I saw one. And - also the old fashioned buses, no tops to. You know. And then as it - as the years went by they had them in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 wheel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 . But it was mostly horses - when I was young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go out visiting neighbours very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No, never - never done that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would neighbours come in to see your father or mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Just - mum and dad you know they used to come in - friends used to come and visit them sometimes, very seldom. 'Cos we were a family used to keep ourselves to ourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would you send out invitations for them to come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Ah - that'd be different. Ah yes, sometimes if there was a - anything special going - they used to send a - and ask - they didn't actually send but they used to come mostly into the shop and he'd invite them. In - to the party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you have many parties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. Not a lot. Not a lot. But when we did have a party we had a party. Used to be wonderful. I can remember it anyway. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did anyone play a musical instrument or sing in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 My mother used to play the piano. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you have a piano in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. The piano - the old fashioned ones you know, with the - candlestick each side. The old fashioned ones. Brass candlesticks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. I - I used to - no I used to - I was taught a couple of lessons - at the piano but of course I learnt meself, I practiced and played by ear. Not by music, I couldn't - I - couple of lessons of music but I couldn't take to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did anyone sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well we all used to sing, you know, all used to get us children to sing. One at a time, brother - my brother will and brother -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You were in the choir weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes, used to sing in the choir. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would you ever bring any choir people home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. No, we used to have to go - to the church and sing. That was in the church where we used to go. In Lincolns Inn Fields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of church was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Pa
rdon? Well it - it was a very - well it was a - a very - high church you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was it Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, Church of England, yes, well it must have been round in Holborn way. I'm trying to think of the name of the church. Can't - can't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You say your father was a Catholic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did he go to the Church of England or would he go to the Catholic church?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No, no, he used to go Church of England with mother. Yes. 'Cos - she wasn't Catholic so - he used to go to church with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How often would they go to Church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Mm - say once a week. That'd be on a Sunday. As I tell you I used to go three times on a Sunday. And I nearly - I think I lived at church. Because my father used to make me go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Were the
re any other organisations you belonged to which were connected with the church or the choir?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. Just used to be - you know, if there was a dance going - when we were young. If - I used to walk - in the processions. The Catholic processions, an
d - we used to go all round the streets. And after that we used to come back and - underneath the church as I told you we used to have a big hall. And we used to have a - nice tea. And a dance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What day of the week would that be on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Pardon? That would be on a Sunday. Sunday evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So they didn't mind dancing on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. No. Those days. And sometimes we used to go Saturdays. Saturday evening. But as I say - I used to go to church on a Saturday and Sunday evenings so therefore you had to be a special - Sunday that they made it, not every Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 They had church on Saturday evening as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Oh yes. Used to have church on a Saturday evening. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was there anything like a Band of Hope you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh y
es, Band of Hope. And - what else was it? Where was it I used to go. Oh needlework classes and all that kind of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 This would be in the night time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Night times. Always evenings, oh it was never during the day because as I say we used to be - schooling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You say your mother and father used to have a lot of books around the house?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Oh yes, shelves of 'em. The old fashioned books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of books were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Mostly the the Victorian days of - you know, the old
 Kings and Queens and all that. And there was another thing that stood out in my mind was - when was the first - I can't remember when the first - coronation was, the first King - it was before mother died I know I must have been about five and there was 
a big coronation, the first King.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Edward VII was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well I can't say about - I can remember going. And I can remember - how my father picked me up and put me on his shoulder to see all the horses and that all go by. But - with the velvet - hats they used to wear those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 That would have been 1910, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 George}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  V wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Must have been something like that, yes. But - oh yes, great fun those days. Well I did anyway. Great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You were allowed to go where you wanted in those times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Not by myself. Oh no, used to - I used to go - Leicester Square, I used to go skating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Ice skating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No, just ordinary skating, we used to go to the church - to the ice - skate ring there, roller skating. And - but I've never done ice skat
ing. Never tried it anyway. I - probably if I'd have learnt it I would - could have done it but I know how to do roller skating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You say you went to all these theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go to the cinema at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Saturday mornings
, penny, used to cost us. That was in Edgware - that was in Euston Road. The picture palace was called the Coloseum, we used to go in for a penny and see the - they used to play the piano. A man downstairs played the piano or the - Pearl White and - all t
hese old fashioned comedy - films, Charlie Chaplin and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What about music halls, did you ever go to the music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes, as I told you I nearly always used to go to nearly all the music halls. See all the - comics - come theatres and all
 that you know, comedies and all that. Laughable things. I think I have been actually to nearly all the theatres down the west end. Princes theatre and - Drury Lane, the Cyceum, Coloseum, Hippodrome - Holborn. Aldgate the - theatre. Oh I think I went to '
em all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go out with just your father on his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Used to go for walks. Just walks, we used to go round the park and Lincoln Inns Fields and that and - and come back and - have tea and then washed and put to bed. But h
e always - he could only take me in the evening, didn't have much time during the day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What time would he finish work in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well I told you, my father never used to like do actual work, he used to get the men to do it. But the shops never used to shut 'til about twelve. Sometimes half past.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 He had to be around to make sure everything was going OK?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
He had to be there - to see that the men were doing their work - right and they'd get the - things in and - you know and put them
 in their right location. You know, whether they kept them downstairs in the - cool room or something, 'cos you know what fruit it. They had to keep it in a certain temperature otherwise it all goes all - funny. So - but he was always there, was always th
e
re for the man and if - another - the other shop before he opened up the other shop, when he was opening it up as I can remember - he had to make the - you know, the alterations and all that - with the - men - that done it, and he was always around if he 
was needed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So he wouldn't have an awful lot of spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No, he didn't, no, no, my father was - what you say actually - when I was a child - I would say it was hard - being on spot at the - moment - when he was needed. I mean - actually he couldn't get his own freedom - most probably when he wanted to.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would he ever belong to any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No never no clubs, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did he ever take an interest in sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 He didn't do any betting or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What about insurance societies, was he ever a member of those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Like sick societies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. Not - that I can remember. No. If he did I don't know nothing at all about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 When - how did your parents spend their spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well they just used to sit - sit in the - what we used to call the - dining room and - read or - perhaps mother'd play the piano or something like that. He'd sit there with her and - enjoyed it. 'Course then it was time really for wa
sh ready for - supper. A glass of milk and - couple of biscuits, then used to be put to bed. Then mother and father'd sit there on their own for a while and then - they used to go to bed theirselves. That's all that I can remember anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would they ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, mum used to read out the picture - the story books. You know, stories. As I say when I started school I know as much as those that went to school quite young. So that way you can see by the character - from the school that - 
I was well advanced - in advance of the - learning. 'Cos when I first started the teacher said I can't - I knew these things, well I said, I was taught by my father and mother - how to read and write.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Were there many newspapers and magazines lying around the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes - they used to have those great big - comics with big pictures on - all funny pictures they used to be, and big reading, and very very large, they used to cost ha'penny. Very large and - about five or six pages in 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of magazines or newspapers would your mother and father have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh just the ordinary books, the ordinary books that was on the shelf they used to read, and newspapers of course. Always had a newspaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Which paper did they take?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh Eve
ning News I think - or the daily paper. The one thing my father did used to like was a bet. Used to get - liked to do - like on the horses. He used to love a bet, and he was very lucky, he used to win. Whether he used to get the tips from my uncle at Newm
arket I couldn't say but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did he ever go to the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes. Yes. And of course he did 'cos he used to sometimes go and see Uncle Fred and - he was - he was right on the race course. In a little cottage, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 where}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  that little cottage is up on the 
slope of the hill there, I can remember that. And - he used to go down there sometimes and - always - always done a bet. 'Cos - when I was down there for two years he used to come down and visit me and - always had a bet. So -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How many evenings a week would you say that your parents }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 stayed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - every - all the week. Except for weekends - when everything was shut they used to - they used to go out. Take us to the country somewhere or other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 They'd drive out in the car?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Sometimes, or they'd have a taxi. But - not always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 They'd take you with them then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of place in the country would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
All round - we used to go round the hopfields. Folkestone. Yes, Folkestone we used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So you went quite a long way out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes, decent - oh was quite a long ride, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Come back the same day would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, never stayed out. But we mostly went - if we did go anywhere we mostly went by bus. And we came by the horse bus. I used to 
like that very much, being on top of the open bus. Yes. Yes. But they used to be very nice those old buses. And the only - there was only one occasion when I was a bit frightened was when - my father decided to go down and see my uncle at Newmarket by bus
.
 And - my mother and father at the front see and I was with them. And it was a wet day. And one of the horses slipped, and of course went down, and - nearly took the bus with it. And we all had to get out and get into another bus, one of the horse - the -
 
one of the horses had hurt their leg as it fell, so that we couldn't get back onto that bus, we had to take another one. I can always remember that, and I was frightened. Yes, it frightened my mother very much, very scared and - after that she said she'd 
never go on a bus again, but she did. I expect I was a bit frightened too although I was young.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did they have many accidents on buses then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. Never many accidents, no. More accidents today than there was those days. Because - ah more, yes, more traffic today is terrific. It's not a - not a patch on when I was a youngster. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would your mother ever go out on her own at all to enjoy herself anywhere?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No. Always with my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Mothers union or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. A
s I tell you she used to - used to go and sit in Lincolns Inn fields and do a bit of crochet or sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
You say your parents were non-drinkers, was there any temperance society in the area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. Not to my knowledge. I can't remember. But I know m
y father and mother never used to drink. And neither did my sister. My sister didn't drink. Yes, neither did my elder sister, she didn't drink. Or smoke. But then my mother never - never smoked, father used to smoke a pipe. One of those clay pipes you kno
w, long - clay pipes. Many a time I've had on - for bubbles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How would you get on with your two brothers and elder sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh lovely. Lovely, we had our own ways, what I wanted I had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did they spoil you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. That was the trouble. And 
- used to be times that if - if I couldn't get what I want I start dancing. 'Til I did get it. Especially with my father. Keep on and on at him, I want this, I want that. He used to say, you're not having it. You hear, what you want, if I haven't got it y
ou're not having it. And then I'd kick. Eventually I'd get it. I'd always go to my father for - anything like that. As I say if I went to mother, she'd say, don't come to me, go to your daddy and ask him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Who would you play with when you were young, wo
uld it be your brothers or would it be neighbours children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - mostly - with my brothers, but I used to play with neighbours children - that was in Leather Lane, dad had a shop in Leather Lane. But I wasn't allowed to go far, I wasn't allowed to 
go out of that lane unless I - had someone with me. I wasn't allowed to go 'cos - in Leather Lane, as you go - if you know Leather Lane, do you know Leather Lane? Go down Leather Lane and you turn out into Gamages don't you, in Holborn that way - that way
. And - may be allowed to go round there and look in the shops but always had to have someone with me. Never allowed on me own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was it as built up then as it is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well I haven't been there dear, I couldn't tell you what it's like now, I haven't been there for ages. Gamages. But it used to be very low those days. Was in like - flat, all the shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 In that area today it's nearly entirely shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No, it used to be - used to be really - I think there used to be about - three shops, two shops, Gamages and another shop, and that used to be on the right hand side I suppose it is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Were they jewelers there in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. They were, in Hatton Garden - oh yes, all in Hatton Gardens all those jewelers. I used to know two or th
ree of 'em in there. And - sometimes my father took me there to one of his customers there and show me - I suppose they were diamonds, I should imagine they were, little tiny bits of - glass things and they used to say it's diamonds, well - those days of 
c
ourse I didn't understand what they meant by diamonds, I thought they were just ordinary beads like you do see today. But if I went to touch - the - a very old man there, and I remember once I went in and I went to touch this - big - bead as I thought. Oh
 
my goodness, he nearly done his nut. Oh don't dare - don't dare touch that 'course it was a diamond. They used to cut - cut them. When they used to buy a ring and cut these diamonds in - what do they call them, chips, cut them in chips. Mm. Little tiny bi
ts, you'd look at them you'd think they were nothing. Think they were just bits you could sweep up throw away glass. Must have cost some money. Mm. I remember that too. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever have any pets or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes. Dog. Cat. As I tell you, 
mice. Told you mice - oh anything, anything I wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Canaries as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Canaries, yes. And rabbits. Oh yes, all those. Oh I got everything I wanted, and my husband used to say I was spoilt. I didn't mind being spoilt, I used to like it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
As I say, at the school we used to. But I never used to go outside in sports. Only at school we used to do the sports. Like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 gymnastics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  and - used to go in like they do you know and - all those kind of things, but always in the school. Never outside.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You didn't play rounders in the street or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would you play in the street in Leather Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - in the garden, oh yes, out in the garden I was always playing I used to mig
ht have a couple of my friends in and play out there. But - as I say if I was allowed outside that - street door you might as well say I wasn't allowed to go from - wherever it was, without being - with somebody. My father would never have that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Would you ever play in neighbours houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Not to my knowledge no. Not that I can remember. I might go inside their passage. That's as far. I would never enter their rooms, never go in their rooms. And father wouldn't - he always used to say I wasn't allowed to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
I don't know. I used to say that you know, we were never allowed to go in the rooms. Whether he thought it was - rude or anything like that I couldn't say, but we were never allowed to go in. Otherwise I had me freedom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did your father ever take any interest in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. Not to my knowledge he didn't no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did he ever vote in general elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well I should imagine so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 But you don't know how he voted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I - no, I couldn't tell you that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You couldn't remember whether your mother was interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. I can't remember that either.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. Never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Can you remember your mother ever being ill before the actual pneumonia?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. I can remember - when - her - the first time mother was taken ill, and I went up and - they called the doctor in. And - that was the first starting of her illness. And - she got better and - she was all right for a couple of ye
ars and - then she had the actual illness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How did you manage while she was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well we used to have somebody in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 This was the same woman who come in normally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes, yes, yes. Used to have a woman that come in and used to do everythin
g - that dad wanted her to do and - of course she had a family herself to look after, that was the idea you see, she had to go out to work. She was very very nice, she was like one of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was she local?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well I don't - I couldn't - she mu
st have been local - to come to - our place. She never used to get on buses or anything so she must have lived - I - I don't know but I think she used to live in - Red Lion Street, Holborn. She come from there somewhere. I'm sure she did, because - my fat
her asked her something one day and - and I did hear her say something about Red Lion Street, I - 'cos when she first came, I can't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4343885\charrsid683676 remember}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676  exactly when she first started for us, but - as I say dad had to ask her where she lived and that and he - 'cos they
 days they only used to pay a small stamp - on a card didn't they, they used to have - I don't know - tuppency stamp or something like that. And dad used to have to put these stamps on her card for her. Because - if you had nothing those days - you had to
 
go without. So - there used to be a scheme of some kind I can't quite recollect that if a card - stamps was put on a card they were allowed to draw a little amount of money. Thos - those days there was really nothing was there. You couldn't go anywhere if
 
you - if you had - say you had nothing and you called anybody in to see if you could get charity - and they saw anything in your place they'd tell you to sell it, get rid of it to get money with. Oh they used to be - like what they used to call a soup kit
c
hen, something for people to go - for a basinful of soup, and there used to be - near Holborn, I think it was in Theobalds Road I can remember, what they used to call a - a lodging house, a doss house they used to call it, for girls and men - for men and 
-
 women, and - I can remember them places there, used to be on the left hand side. I think it was called Rowton House that was. That was called Rowton House and - that was for the men. And - I don't know what the name of the other house was for the women, 
but always used - all used to combine together, men one side, women the other.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
You that people divided society into different groups in that age, what would you say were the different groups or social classes that were around before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I don't quite get what you mean by that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
You described these people that had to go to the doss house or people who had charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 They would be the very poor people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Who would be the other groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - the other - the other people would be that they've got - sufficient to live on, they can manage. But people that used to go in these places had nothing at all. Nowhere to sleep and no money for - getting food. So therefore they used t
o go and sleep in these places and they used to supply them with soup. Bowls of soup. And then they might give them a little - what they used to call a little voucher. Paper - thing - get them something to eat during the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What class or what group would these people belong to would you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh very very poor. Very poor, what they call tramps. Girls that - perhaps - what you might say are not much - good. And spend their time with a men and you know, and - go to these places - 'cos I suppose 
- well what could you say - they didn't do good they had to go somewhere to sleep. I mean, that was the kind of people they used to have there. Ragged people. Those sort of people, I've seen them go in. All the men and - and awful some of the girls that u
s
ed to go in there. More often than not with my father if I've gone by there some time, I've seen them go in there. And to me it's - never used to say anything, never passed a remark to my father but - I used to look at them and me, I used to say to myself
 - oh, how dirty. See. So that's a bit - I don't even know if it's still there now, it could be, what they used to-call Rowton House. That was in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What was the general attitude towards people like this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 My - my - I'd never mix with them would I. I wouldn't know them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I mean amongst yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh - quite all right. My father used to class anybody like that, he was quite - as he might be - to you or myself. He - he wouldn't treat 'em no different and matter of fact - well I have seen m
y father - give - give 'em something in their hand, they used to come begging - he'd give 'em something - in their hand, get themselves something with. Oh my father was a very generous man, matter of fact he was too generous. And my mother was just the sa
me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Was there anybody at that time that you'd say, oh she's a real lady or he's a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. There's a big hotel on the corner of Ann Court, you know, I don't know if it's still there now, a big hotel? Well - when I was quite young, as 
I say, when they had that shop in Ann Court here, there used to be a gentleman and a lady go up in car there every week, used to go into this hotel. And - one day I was standing at - the shop door like - and - this gentleman came up, and lady and - starte
d
 talking to me. And I can remember it plainly, he picked me up and he must have been a thorough gentleman, and picked me up and nursed me for a while and - he took me into the hotel, asked my father if he - could take me into this hotel. Oh a huge long pl
a
ce, I'd never been in - can remember it since, but huge long place, beautiful carpets, and I don't know what the hotel was called, whether it's a - residence for people to stay or not I don't know but I know he had a beautiful car and all, and he used to 
- he used to come here every week. And he always used to come to the door of the shop and speak to me, and ask me if I'd like to go \{BLANK\}
 He would never allow me to go again. 'Cos he made a habit of it. And whether my father got the wrong impression or no
t I don't know. But he wouldn't allow it but - and always used to give me some money in my hand, I could never tell you now what it was because I was too young. But it was all - I know it was silver of some sort. Whether they - wanted to take me or not I 
don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was there anybody you called sir or master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. I think I used to call my father sir. I'm not - I got the habit of it you know. Everybody here now - it comes - when I used to serve the dinners downstairs - it's always sir, y
ou know, they look at me a bit old fashioned, as much as to say that's funny, I say to them I'm sorry but I've been so used to that way of speaking, yes sir or madam and - when I got older of course - working in shops, Marks and Spencers - when I got marr
i
ed, I was shop assistant, it was always sir and madam - when you're behind the counter, and - oh yes, I even call my father sir. Yes sir. And - he said that he - he used to say to me that's the right way to pronounce - or speak to anyone or talking to any
body in your own class. Always used to tell me that. So - that's how it -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What group would you say you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - I should say - I belonged to the second group wouldn't you. I wouldn't say - I say we wasn't poor. I wasn't rich. But I had - everything that I wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So there's the very rich, the rich and the poor are there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Rich. Well I'd be the rich then of course they'd be poor wouldn't they.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Amongst the poor were they all the same level of poor, or were there sort of steps of poverty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh steps of poverty, some of the - as I say, some of them spent money - drinking, and some would earn enough to be comfortable - comfortable. And some'd manage on just what they got and some'd have nothing. And - it - people living ne
xt to us or anywhere near us, if my father thought they were a bit on the - short side, I say, he often used to - if they come in fro fruit or - potatoes or anything like that - and perhaps they'd come in and say can we leave it 'til next week, father use
d
 to do that, he'd say, all right, leave it, don't worry about it, leave it. He never used to go around saying, you owe me this and you owe me that. If he thought they hadn't - and I think he - he let them carry on and - take no more notice, but he wouldn'
t let it go too far, because some of the people used to make a habit of it. Yes. That's what they used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Were you brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. You treat them all the same. Mixed with everybod
y my father used to say. No matter what class of people you were with - nobody's - any different to anybody else. We're all equal he used to say. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What sort of people belonged to the very rich people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How would you describe them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - what could you say - those type of people don't talk much do they unless they - take a liking to you. If they took a liking to you like that gentleman did to me, he spoke. But you mustn't speak to him first. You had to wait 'til
 they speak to you. And - he was very nice and must have had plenty of money. And the lady. She wore all these furs and all that you know and - went into this hotel and - took me in, he took me all over it. And then brought me back to my father. And put m
o
ney in me hand, I didn't want it really. My father said, no, you mustn't do that. But he would persist, this man. Well I had to take it. But he always used to make it a habit. And my father - whatever he got - I don't know what passed his mind, but - he s
topped it. The gentleman stopped all of a sudden. Said, no, she mustn't go no more. What is that hotel called by the way? Have you - a hotel, if you say you've seen it? On the corner of Ann.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I don't know, I'm not sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 It's a big enormous big pl
ace it was, enormous big hotel. It used to run along into - Ann Court and half - into Holborn. No, you're not that way, no, well I do, I know all that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Who would be the most important people in your area then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 In my?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Where you lived in 
Holborn, who would be the most important people in that neighbourhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - I couldn't tell you that. I'm sure. No, not at all. No I don't know about that, see, I couldn't tell you that at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What about the doctors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Ah - well - Harley Street for one isn't it. He - he's a big doctor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Wasn't that in the West End?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 I mean the actual area where you lived, who would be the most important people

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well the doctor of course. Doctor, wouldn't he because - I mean he wa
s quite local - for the district, and he would be the important man - for - for anything serious, accident and they took - take the people into there right away - before - ever ambulance came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What about people like the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well, yes. The cl
ergy would be - one important person. But - he would be the - for religion of course. Protestant and Catholic, but - they all had their own - we used to have - call 'em fathers, and the Protestants used to call 'em just the bishop. Where we could say - Ou
r Lady, the Catholics, they say Virgin Mary. See?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you ever go to a Catholic church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. Yes. I told you I - I used to - I was confirmed in a Catholic church and - and - take confession and - Holy Communion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 As well as going to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes, as well as going to the church, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 So you went to the two when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes, that's right, both of them, mm. 'Cos my mother's Church of England and - the Catholic one. But I'm mostly Roman Catholic. Even when I grew up big and I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Which was the one you were member of the choir in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. Church of England. That was in Leicester Square.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Where was the Catholic church you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 The Catholic church is in Judge Street. And it's still there t
oo. That church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What kind of people went to the High Church then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh - just ordinary people you know. Ordinary people, Catholic people, and sometimes they used to get Protestants in the Catholic, they would seem to prefer the Catholic religion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Do you remember seeing a policeman around in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
The only time I can remember the policemen is when they used to go round blowing whistles if there were air raids. That's the only time I can remember policeman coming blowing whistles on
 their bikes. Telling you to take cover something like. Or if there was a fire or anything like that. And the muffin man and all that. And - that's the only time I remember policeman, I can't remember anything else about a policeman. Their uniforms were d
ifferent of course what they have today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You don't remember seeing many around the area?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No, not many policemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Was your home rented or was it your own home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No, it was rented. Shop was rented and the house was rented.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you see much of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you see much of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. If - I never - if - if he came I don't know who was - I was never introduced to him as a - child. That wasn't my affair, my father did anything but - it was nothing to do with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
You say that you used to go to dances and things like that. Did life change much after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You were a bit older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh - oh yes, after I left school of course - I got older, I got more understanding. A
nd - my father would allow me to go to the dances with a - nice - young man most probably, somebody even that had got - business people that had got a shop. And there used to be one young man I was very keen on, used to go in the car for me - he used to g
o to the - well any dance that was going. He'd allow me to go - providing I was back to the proper time. But - if I - I over did it - he used to stop me. But - I never did, I always used to get back on time. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 What time would you have to be back by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh - about a half - eleven thirty. Never allow me to stop 'til twelve. The dances used to go on some time those days all night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. Oh yes, and the clubs dances used to go on all night, in those days. Oh I can remember my fath
er telling me about it. He used to say sometimes, I think it's disgusting. The way some of you girls - stay out very late at night. I don't know what their parents are thinking of. See? Always had that impression on him. Got to be very careful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 You say you didn't do any work except help around the shop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No. After I got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 We've already got what you did after you got married on the tape.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. Never done anything 'til I got married. And then when I got married as I say - th
en I didn't work for years while I had the children. I only worked started work when the boys got old enough to go to school. And I used to do about two or three hours - and come home, so I was there and - fetch 'em from school and - take them to school. 
I'd be there when they come home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
After you left school did you ever regret - did you do evening classes after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. I used to go for - what did I do evening classes - oh dressmaking. I used to go to evening classes for. And learn
 to make dresses or - things like that. 'Cos I can cut out and make anything, or any - or I mostly do anything. I could put me hand to it. Whether it was a success or not I don't know, but I've seen me - I seemed to be able to do - majority to anything, e
ngineering or - practically the only thing I can't do is printing. And that my husband tried to show me how to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
While you were at school did your parents show much interest in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Oh yes. Oh yes, we used to - fetch - I used to fe
tch home my paper of an evening and show them the report. And then they were all pleased with it, as you see by the character you can't go - you - you - you must know by that character that - what kind of person I was at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did they ever see the teachers much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
No. No. But - I think - my father and mother did used to go - go up there say - about month every three months, something like that. If there was anything special going. And they - they used to come up. The school then. Reports and - b
ut of course those - those days we always used to have the report sent home - to the parents. If there was anything that they thought wasn't right-they used to have to go up, but my parents never used to have to. I was always -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 How often would you work in the shop when you were just helping out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Well - I used to help my father - when it - was inconvenient for him. If he found that it - he had to do something he used to go and ask me to go in the shop and - serve up. The people used - he had outsi
de and inside - fruit. I used to be able to - read the - tills and of course those days it was just weighing with scales, the price scales you know you put 'em - pound - two pound or three pounds. Not like today ready reckoners. But see it was quite simpl
e.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you get paid for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh pocket money. That's all - you never used to have the pocket I used to take what I'd want. I used to be able to take out the till what I wanted. He used to tell me my father I've taken all his profit. Always used
 to tell me that. You've robbed me of all my profit. I'll have nothing, I'll be ruined.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Do you think once you left school that people treated you any differently?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. They was always nice to me, always nice to my parents too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 It didn't 
change your relationships with people, with your father or your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you still go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 After you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 After I left school. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you still go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Mm. Holy Cross.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did you have any special friends at this time after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Yes. I had one girl friend here name was - oh gosh, forgotten the name now, her name - well - Eddie Burrows. And - if we went dancing or anything like that we always used
 to - always be together. And - as we got older we of course got boyfriends. And - she couldn't read or write. She couldn't. So I used to have to write all her love letters to her boyfriends. When she used to get one back I used to read 'em out to her. It
 
was really funny and - he was a well educated lad and - used to live a long way away and when he did come up to see - first time he came up - see Eddie - of course - she said to me, well what am I going to do here, she said. I said, oh I don't know, she s
a
id, well - I don't know - what to say, 'cos - you wrote all the letters to him and you answered all the letters. She said, I shall look a fool. 'Course when he started to speak to her and he found that she - couldn't read or write he wanted to know how sh
e
 used to write the letters. Of course I was introduced to him. And when I was introduced to him of course he fell for me and - you know. But I didn't like that at all but - always used to be asking about me. So he give Edie up. Shame, 'cos he was a very n
i
ce lad, very nice boy. She was very upset about it. So I said, there you are, your fault, you should have learnt to read and write, why didn't you learn to read and write. She went to school but she was a very - bad scholar. She - she couldn't reckon up o
r
 anything like that. And to ask her a word, to spell a word it was impossible, she couldn't do it. So I used to sit and - and we used to do it - her parents went out, she'd say, you come in and answer the letter when mum's gone out, and I used to write le
t
ters to him. And then when he used to answer - I used to answer again. I got fed up with it at the finish. I said, you've got to learn write, and he's trying to learn her to read and write. But, no, she - didn't seem as though she was interested in it any
way. Learning.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did your father meet these friends of yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes. Oh yes. But - as I say - in Judge street there used to be a - a pub facing - and he was a very nice boy, handsome looking boy, very keen on me, he had a lovely car and all, well
 - lovely to those days you know what the cars were. To me it was lovely. Yes. Some of the - pub. And - used to go out and about, dancing and that but I was really sweet on him. And of course - when I got to the age of - sixteen - I met my husband. And - 
o
h well he came and saw my father and - asked could he take me out so - I liked him at first and then I - oh I don't like you. Anyway, somehow we became engaged. I was engaged for two years. I used to take his ring off - go dancing with another boyfriend. 
H
e used to be searching for me. I used to go with the boy in the pub. Where I used to live, used to go all that way right down to - Judge Street, not Judge Street - yes, Judge Street - to meet him. I used to go dancing with him. Oh I used to have lots of b
oyfriends. Sailors and - then I got married to my husband after all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7892935 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 Did your father expect to know where you were all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9010046 LW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13049666\charrsid683676 
Oh yes, he used to say to me, where did you get to, where have you been? His my husband's name was Joe. Joe's be
en here and he - he promised - you'd meet him, be in here at so and so time. My father never liked my husband. He never wanted me to marry him. No, I don't know for what reason, but - he used to say to me, I don't like him. I think it was because my husba
n
d likes drink. Well - of course when I married my hubby - U - I didn't know, it wasn't drunkard or anything like that. But - never being in with the drinking - my father used to think it was terrible - that he should drink, and I used to say to my father 
w
ell you must understand - well it doesn't mean to say he's bad daddy, I used to say, could be a - a nice fellow, which he was. So - the only thing was he had a bit of a temper. And - when he used to want to go out, but I always had to be with him. Where h
e
 was I had to be. And - if I was doing anything in the house - putting curtains up or anything like that and he came in, perhaps he might have a - day off or couple of days off like what they owed him, I'd have to drop everything to get ready to go out. S
o - but then I got that I - when the kiddies come along as I say - you couldn't do that. You couldn't drop everything and go out.
\par }}